  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ handle acknowledgments differently:\n\n1. **Go-Back-N ARQ: Cumulative Acknowledgments**\n   - **Mechanism:** In Go-Back-N, the receiver sends a single acknowledgment (ACK) for the highest sequence number of the correctly received, in-order packet. This ACK implicitly acknowledges all preceding packets as well.\n   - **Example:** If packets 1 through 5 are sent and packets 1 through 3 are received correctly, but packet 4 is lost, the receiver will acknowledge packet 3. The sender, upon not receiving an ACK for packet 4 within a timeout, will retransmit packet 4 and all subsequent packets (5, etc.), even if some were received correctly.\n\n2. **Selective Repeat ARQ: Individual Acknowledgments**\n   - **Mechanism:** Selective Repeat allows the receiver to acknowledge each correctly received packet individually, regardless of order. This means the receiver can acknowledge packets out of sequence and only retransmit the specific packets that were lost or corrupted.\n   - **Example:** If packets 1 through 5 are sent and packet 3 is lost, the receiver can acknowledge packets 1, 2, 4, and 5 individually. The sender will only retransmit packet 3, rather than all subsequent packets.\n\n**Summary:**\n- **Go-Back-N ARQ** uses **cumulative acknowledgments**, acknowledging the receipt of all packets up to a certain point.\n- **Selective Repeat ARQ** uses **individual acknowledgments**, allowing for more precise retransmission of only the missing or corrupted packets.\n\nThis distinction affects the efficiency and reliability of data transmission, especially in environments with higher error rates.\n\n**References:**\n- Stallings, W. (2013). *Data and Computer Communications*. Pearson.\n- Kurose, J. F., & Ross, K. W. (2017). *Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach*. Pearson.\n\n**Note:** The choice between Go-Back-N and Selective Repeat depends on the specific requirements and constraints of the network environment, such as error rates and the need for efficient bandwidth usage.\n\n**Answer Summary:**\nGo-Back-N ARQ sends cumulative acknowledgments for the highest in-order packet received, while Selective Repeat ARQ sends individual acknowledgments for each specific packet. Thus, Go-Back-N uses cumulative acknowledgements, and Selective Repeat uses acknowledgements for every individual packet.",
